<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-04-15T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-04-15T16:00:00-05:00" n="569" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d569">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">815.00 Revolutions/511: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Keena</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-15T15:00:00-06:00">April 15, 1936—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 7:03 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>41. Referring to Department’s telegram No. 22, April 14, 7 p.m. The
                            suggestion I made in telegram No. 39, April 11, noon, concerning a naval
                            vessel cruising in the vicinity of Honduras was based on the belief that
                            the moral effect would be good in the event of an outbreak of
                            hostilities on the north coast. The suggestion was not prompted by nor
                            communicated to either the Honduran authorities or any American
                            citizen.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Keena</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>